## 🌐 1. HTTP — The Web's Foundation

Application-layer, client-server request-response model.

### HTTP Methods

| Method | Purpose |
|---|---|
| **GET** | Request data (safe, idempotent) |
| **POST** | Submit data to be processed (not idempotent) |
| **PUT** | Upload/replace a resource |
| **DELETE** | Delete a resource |
| **HEAD** | Get headers only, no body |
| **OPTIONS** | Describe communication options |
| **PATCH** | Partial modification of a resource |

### HTTP Status Codes

| Range | Meaning | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| 1xx | Informational | — |
| 2xx | Success | 200 OK, 201 Created, 204 No Content |
| 3xx | Redirection | 301 Moved Permanently, 302 Found |
| 4xx | Client Error | 400 Bad Request, 401 Unauthorized, 403 Forbidden, 404 Not Found |
| 5xx | Server Error | 500 Internal Server Error, 503 Service Unavailable |

### Headers
- **Request:** `User-Agent`, `Accept`, `Cookie`, `Authorization`
- **Response:** `Content-Type`, `Set-Cookie`, `Cache-Control`, `Server`

### HTTP Version Evolution

| Version | Key Feature |
|---|---|
| HTTP/1.0 | Basic — new connection per request |
| HTTP/1.1 | Persistent connections (keep-alive), pipelining, host headers |
| HTTP/2 | Multiplexing, header compression, server push, binary framing |
| HTTP/3 | Runs over **QUIC** (UDP-based) — reduces head-of-line blocking |

