## 🛠️ Practical Walkthroughs

### 1. DNS Resolution
```bash
nslookup www.google.com      # Windows
dig www.google.com           # macOS/Linux
```
Shows resolved IP(s) + which DNS server answered. Try:
```bash
dig mx google.com            # mail exchanger records
```

### 2. DHCP-Assigned Configuration
```bash
ipconfig /all        # Windows — shows DHCP server + lease times
ifconfig              # macOS
ip addr show          # Linux
```
Confirms IP, subnet mask, gateway, DNS servers assigned dynamically.

### 3. ARP Cache
```bash
arp -a        # Windows/macOS/Linux
ip neigh      # Linux alternative
```
Shows IP→MAC mappings your device has learned — should include your default gateway.

### 4. HTTP Headers (Browser DevTools)
1. Open DevTools (F12) → Network tab
2. Visit `http://neverssl.com` (plain HTTP demo site)
3. Click the main document request → Headers tab
4. Observe request headers (`User-Agent`, `Accept`, `Host`) and response headers (`Content-Type`, `Server`, status line)

### 5. HTTPS Headers (Browser DevTools)
1. Same DevTools setup, visit `https://www.google.com`
2. Note `HTTP/2 200 OK` (or HTTP/3), modern headers like `Sec-CH-UA`
3. Actual payload is encrypted in transit — DevTools can show it decrypted because your browser holds the session keys from the TLS handshake

